The next sentence contains great difficul- ties. Halm says “ verba imperatori et cum suerit . . . doloris mei auctore Garatonio in Curis Sec. ad Plancianam p. 60 ut spuria significavi.'’ This is a short way of settling the difficulty.

Markland says correctly that a man did not get a Quaestor in his capacity of Imperat0r3 nor had Cicero yet had the title of Impera- tor. He only got it some years later when he was governor of Cilicia, and had ob- tained some victories over the mountaineers of the Amanus. Markland conjectures that the writer of this speech did not know the difference between Imperator and ⁴ esse cum imperio‚' which was said generally of a provincial governor. But whatever error there is in the use of Imperator here, we can hardly suppose that the writer of this speech did not know what Imperator meant, and the difference between that word and the expres- sion ‘cum imperio esse.' Gesner’s answer is that what Cicero says, ‘si mihi quaestor imperatori fuisset‚' is said hypothetically3 but still the question is why Imperatori, and not Praetori or Consuli, which would
